<TITLE> Huda petition returned </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 28 (bdnews24)The High Court on Monday returned a petition by former minster Nazmul Huda challenging the Election Commission's decision to disqualify those convicted under emergency powers rules from participating in any election, even if their case is under appeal. Huda, a former communications minister of the four-party alliance government, filed the petition Sunday, citing article 66 of the Constitution, which outlines the eligibility of prospective candidates to the Jatiya Sangsad elections. According to existing laws of the country, anyone convicted to over two years in prison is ineligible to contest elections for a further five years from the date of their release, unless an appeal is pending with the High Court. According to the EPR, any person convicted for any term under the rules is ineligible to participate in any local body or national election, even if an appeal is pending with the High Court. Former communications minister Nazmul Huda filed a petition with the High Court on Sunday, arguing that the EC's move to bar those with an appeal pending in the upper court runs contrary to the Constitution. The bench of justice Syed Mahmud Hossain and justice Kamrul Islam returned the petition on Monday, citing time constraints, as any ruling requiring a constitutional explanation would require the court to appoint amicus curi . bdnew
